<div id="review_3990962891" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3990962891" />
    <a title="Leslie Ray" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34974046-leslie-ray"><img alt="Leslie Ray" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1410712047p2/34974046.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3990962891?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leslie Ray" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leslie Ray" href="/user/show/34974046-leslie-ray">Leslie Ray</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780062074119" href="/book/show/11181295-the-pale-horse">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3990962891" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3479573456360413150">This was originally published in 1962, but was quite advanced with an almost &quot;quantum theory&quot; of murder implied. A very likeable protagonist, Mark Easterbrook becomes quite curious about the murder of a priest who has visited a woman on her deathbed. The clever priest hid a list of names that she gave him which the brutal killer searched for but could not find on the priest. There comes to light in this killing a connection to The Pale Horse, a public house run by three women rumored to be pract</span>
  <span id="freeText3479573456360413150" style="display:none">This was originally published in 1962, but was quite advanced with an almost "quantum theory" of murder implied. A very likeable protagonist, Mark Easterbrook becomes quite curious about the murder of a priest who has visited a woman on her deathbed. The clever priest hid a list of names that she gave him which the brutal killer searched for but could not find on the priest. There comes to light in this killing a connection to The Pale Horse, a public house run by three women rumored to be practices of the dark arts and occult. With the help of his friend, Ginger, Mark comes up with a way to get to the bottom of this twisted and somewhat eerie mystery, of murder by "suggestion".<br />This was a true mystery with surprise whodunnit. I loved the twist at the end. The Miss Marple and Hercule Poirot mysteries are so well known, but there are standalones of Agatha Christie, such as this one, that deserve a look by mystery enthusiasts.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3479573456360413150" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


